WEBVTT

00:00.834 --> 00:02.884
Morton’s dishonored
my daughter.

00:03.003 --> 00:05.013
‐ They can’t stay here.
‐ JAMIE: Ye’ll leave at dawn.

00:05.088 --> 00:07.378
The lass has smallpox.
Throw her overboard.

00:07.508 --> 00:08.428
‐ Please don’t.
‐ [ screams ]

00:08.509 --> 00:09.679
Have you lost your mind?

00:09.760 --> 00:11.180
And I’ll do the same for any

00:11.261 --> 00:12.641
who show signs of a rash.

00:12.721 --> 00:13.851
I can help keep you hidden.

00:13.931 --> 00:15.931
‐ I dinna ken your name.
‐ Roger.

00:16.016 --> 00:18.226
‐ Morag MacKenzie.
‐ I’m a MacKenzie as well.

00:18.352 --> 00:21.482
I must admit,
I have grown quite fond
of North Carolina.

00:21.563 --> 00:22.653
Pain me to leave it in chaos.

00:22.731 --> 00:23.821
And farmers though we be,

00:23.899 --> 00:25.819
we’ve beat our plowshares
into swords

00:25.901 --> 00:27.441
and are training for battle.

00:27.528 --> 00:28.528
How many men do ye have?

00:28.654 --> 00:30.454
Go to it, lads.

00:30.531 --> 00:31.661
[ dramatic music ]

00:31.740 --> 00:33.070
The Regulators are
disorganized.

00:33.200 --> 00:35.950
No way prepared for war
against the Crown.

00:36.662 --> 00:37.702
I had hoped it wouldn’t
come to this,

00:37.829 --> 00:39.709
but it seems we’re gonna have
our war after all.

00:43.877 --> 00:45.837
CHOIR:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

00:45.921 --> 00:49.261
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

00:49.383 --> 00:51.513
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

00:51.593 --> 00:54.603
♪ Be I? ♪

00:54.721 --> 00:56.721
♪ Merry of soul ♪

00:56.848 --> 00:59.768
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

00:59.893 --> 01:01.773
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:01.895 --> 01:04.935
♪ To Skye ♪

01:05.065 --> 01:07.685
♪ Billow and breeze ♪

01:07.776 --> 01:10.486
♪ Islands and seas ♪

01:10.571 --> 01:13.161
♪ Mountains of rain and sun ♪

01:13.240 --> 01:15.740
♪ Mountains of rain
and sun ♪

01:15.826 --> 01:18.406
♪ All that was good ♪

01:18.495 --> 01:20.745
♪ All that was fair ♪

01:20.831 --> 01:23.251
♪ All that was me ♪

01:23.375 --> 01:25.845
♪ Is gone ♪

01:25.919 --> 01:28.459
♪ Sing me a song ♪

01:28.589 --> 01:31.299
♪ Of a lass that is gone ♪

01:31.425 --> 01:33.435
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

01:33.510 --> 01:36.430
♪ Be I? ♪

01:36.555 --> 01:38.565
♪ Merry of soul ♪

01:38.640 --> 01:41.520
♪ She sailed on a day ♪

01:41.602 --> 01:45.812
♪ Over the sea ♪

01:45.939 --> 01:51.819
♪ To Skye ♪

01:51.945 --> 01:55.115
[ dramatic music ]

01:55.240 --> 01:57.160
♪

01:57.284 --> 02:01.624
WOMAN:
♪ Sing me a song ♪

02:01.705 --> 02:04.295
♪ Of a lass ♪

02:04.374 --> 02:07.344
♪ That is gone ♪

02:07.461 --> 02:11.551
♪ Say, could that lass ♪

02:11.632 --> 02:13.972
♪ Be I? ♪

02:14.926 --> 02:16.796
CLAIRE:
We went to Hillsborough ready

02:16.928 --> 02:18.968
for what outcome,
we couldn’t know.

02:19.097 --> 02:21.977
But a good soldier is taught
to be prepared,

02:22.100 --> 02:25.940
ready to fight,
and ready to die if need be.

02:26.021 --> 02:28.061
But what no one
can prepare for

02:28.148 --> 02:31.358
is to face family
in the time of war.

02:31.485 --> 02:34.535
ROGER:
♪ Drove she ducklings
to the water ♪

02:34.655 --> 02:37.205
♪ Every morning,
just at nine ♪

02:37.324 --> 02:40.084
♪ Hit her foot
against a splinter ♪

02:40.160 --> 02:43.040
♪ Fell into the foaming brine ♪

02:43.163 --> 02:45.173
♪ Oh, my darling,
oh, my darling ♪

02:45.248 --> 02:48.708
♪ Oh, my darling Clementine ♪

02:48.835 --> 02:51.085
♪ You are lost
and gone forever ♪

02:51.171 --> 02:54.261
♪ Dreadful sorry, Clementine ♪

02:54.341 --> 02:56.631
[ Jemmy coos ]

02:56.718 --> 02:58.718
That’s all for today, laddie.

02:58.845 --> 03:01.095
Your da has to go.

03:01.181 --> 03:05.191
But I promise I will be back
to sing it again for you.

03:05.310 --> 03:08.060
He never gets tired
of that one.

03:08.980 --> 03:11.440
I still wish you’d stayed
at the Ridge.

03:11.525 --> 03:15.035
I wanted to be as close to you
as I could for as long as
possible.

03:15.112 --> 03:17.362
Lizzie, Jemmy,
and I will be safe

03:17.489 --> 03:19.449
here in Hillsborough
with the Sherstons.

03:19.533 --> 03:22.043
I’d better get on the road.
The Colonel will be
expecting me.

03:22.703 --> 03:25.253
Come now,
we’ll get breakfast.

03:30.419 --> 03:32.549
You know, if we were
back in Oxford in our own time,

03:32.629 --> 03:34.589
we’d be making our lunchboxes

03:34.715 --> 03:36.055
and seeing each other off
to work.

03:36.133 --> 03:38.893
Now here I am seeing you off
to war.

03:40.387 --> 03:42.467
[ solemn music ]

03:42.556 --> 03:44.096
Come here.

03:44.224 --> 03:47.104
♪

03:51.356 --> 03:53.896
I barely knew my father
before he was killed
in World War II.

03:55.068 --> 03:57.108
And Jemmy is much younger
than I was.

03:58.947 --> 04:00.027
If I don’t make it back...

04:00.115 --> 04:03.915
Hey, that is not
going to happen.

04:05.078 --> 04:06.868
And while you are gone,
I will tell him

04:06.955 --> 04:10.205
how brave his father is.

04:12.627 --> 04:14.087
Maybe we’ll be lucky.

04:14.171 --> 04:16.261
Maybe Billy Tryon will
come to his senses

04:16.381 --> 04:18.721
and work things out peacefully
with these Regulators.

04:18.800 --> 04:22.100
♪

04:34.649 --> 04:37.149
But just in case, you know
all the words to "Clementine"?

04:37.277 --> 04:40.197
[ laughs ]
Yes, but I’m no singer,

04:40.280 --> 04:44.200
so you had better keep
your promise to your son.

04:44.284 --> 04:47.584
♪

04:47.662 --> 04:49.162
Good‐bye, Roger Mac.

04:49.956 --> 04:51.746
Good‐bye, Mrs. Mac.

04:51.833 --> 04:55.133
♪

05:09.810 --> 05:11.480
[ door closes ]

05:24.950 --> 05:27.240
‐ Hmm?
‐ Happy birthday, Colonel.

05:32.749 --> 05:34.459
You taking stock?

05:34.543 --> 05:36.883
[ both laugh ]

05:37.003 --> 05:38.553
Something of the sort.

05:40.048 --> 05:42.258
Well, I suppose I have
a few hours left.

05:44.135 --> 05:46.675
I was born at half‐six.

05:47.472 --> 05:50.312
I willna have lived
a half‐century
until suppertime.

05:50.392 --> 05:51.522
Oh.

05:51.601 --> 05:54.271
Do you expect to disintegrate
much before then?

05:54.354 --> 05:56.484
Do you need me
to fetch you a cane?

05:56.565 --> 05:57.615
[ groans ]

05:57.691 --> 05:58.691
Or a hearing trumpet?

05:58.817 --> 06:01.437
‐ Hmm?
‐ [ laughs ]

06:02.362 --> 06:05.072
I dinna suppose anything’s
likely to fall off before then.

06:05.949 --> 06:07.449
As for the workings...

06:07.534 --> 06:08.744
‐ Oh.
‐ Huh.

06:08.869 --> 06:11.449
‐ Well...
‐ It all seems to be
in perfect working order.

06:11.538 --> 06:14.038
‐ Huh.
‐ There’s nothing loose at all.

06:14.165 --> 06:15.575
‐ Uh‐huh.
‐ [ laughs ]

06:15.709 --> 06:17.129
Good.

06:19.004 --> 06:20.424
How did ye ken
what I was doing?

06:21.882 --> 06:24.132
"Taking stock," as ye say.

06:26.011 --> 06:30.391
I do it too
before every birthday.

06:31.516 --> 06:33.016
Hmm.

06:33.101 --> 06:36.691
I like to reflect
on the year past.

06:36.771 --> 06:38.521
I think everybody does.

06:39.566 --> 06:41.896
Just making sure that
you’re the same person

06:42.027 --> 06:43.567
as you were the day before.

06:46.615 --> 06:49.785
Ye dinna see
any marked changes,
do ye, Sassenach?

06:53.997 --> 06:56.207
‐ Hmm?
‐ No.

06:58.919 --> 07:00.419
[ whispers ]
You’re still you.

07:04.090 --> 07:07.300
[ tender music ]

07:07.427 --> 07:10.297
♪

07:16.061 --> 07:18.981
It struck me...

07:19.105 --> 07:23.275
I’ve now lived
longer than my father did.

07:25.153 --> 07:27.823
Now this is a morning
he never saw.

07:27.948 --> 07:29.368
He died when he was 49.

07:29.449 --> 07:33.449
I’m sure he’d be happy to know
you’re alive...

07:33.536 --> 07:37.706
with children and grandchildren
that love you.

07:37.791 --> 07:40.421
Aye, mo chridhe.

07:42.462 --> 07:45.382
The world and each day in it
is a gift.

07:45.465 --> 07:47.175
Hmm.

07:47.300 --> 07:51.350
Whatever tomorrow brings,
I’m grateful to see it.

07:54.182 --> 07:57.102
And as for taking stock,
I’ve all my teeth...

07:57.185 --> 07:59.305
‐ Mm‐hmm.
‐ None of my parts are missing,

07:59.437 --> 08:02.397
and my cock still stands up
by itself in the morning.

08:03.483 --> 08:05.783
Could be worse.
[ groans softly ]

08:05.860 --> 08:08.650
♪

08:08.780 --> 08:09.910
Hmm.

08:09.990 --> 08:12.740
♪

08:12.826 --> 08:15.996
♪ Happy birthday to you ♪

08:16.121 --> 08:18.251
[ chuckles ]

08:20.834 --> 08:23.674
♪ Happy birthday ♪

08:26.297 --> 08:28.507
‐ ♪ To you ♪
‐ Oh.

08:30.135 --> 08:34.015
♪ Happy birthday,
dear Colonel ♪

08:34.097 --> 08:35.677
[ moans softly ]

08:35.807 --> 08:37.387
♪ Happy...♪

08:39.352 --> 08:41.152
[ both breathing heavily ]

08:41.229 --> 08:42.859
CLAIRE: ♪ Birthday ♪

08:42.939 --> 08:46.399
♪ To you ♪

08:46.526 --> 08:49.396
♪

08:55.827 --> 08:58.367
GOVERNOR TRYON:
General Gage was good enough
to send two field pieces

08:58.496 --> 09:00.366
and six swivel guns
from New York.

09:00.457 --> 09:01.957
These insurgents
wanted a fight,

09:02.042 --> 09:03.292
and they shall have one.

09:06.129 --> 09:07.549
How many men do we have,
Your Excellency?

09:07.630 --> 09:11.090
Uh, counting your company,
Colonel Fraser, 1,068.

09:11.217 --> 09:13.217
Colonel Moore will command
the artillery,

09:13.303 --> 09:14.643
Colonel Leech, the infantry.

09:14.721 --> 09:16.311
Captain Bullock’s here
with the cavalry.

09:16.389 --> 09:17.559
They’re camped
around the river bend.

09:17.682 --> 09:18.812
COLONEL CHADWICK:
Uh, that’s not accounting

09:18.892 --> 09:20.142
for General Waddell’s brigade.

09:20.226 --> 09:21.686
He’s at Salisbury,
awaiting the arrival

09:21.770 --> 09:24.230
of two wagonloads
of gunpowder from Charleston.

09:25.565 --> 09:26.725
Sir.

09:30.070 --> 09:33.700
The Regulators willna have
artillery and munitions
of this caliber.

09:33.782 --> 09:36.702
They’re mostly farmers
with no military training.

09:36.785 --> 09:38.915
Something they should be
mindful to consider

09:39.037 --> 09:40.247
before provoking the Crown.

09:40.371 --> 09:43.121
I trust your men are all
in order, Colonel Fraser?

09:43.249 --> 09:44.919
Aye, they’re ready, sir.

09:45.043 --> 09:46.673
Hmm.

09:46.753 --> 09:49.673
[ dramatic music ]

09:49.756 --> 09:51.416
[ horse whinnies ]

09:56.930 --> 09:58.890
Well done, Colonel.

09:58.973 --> 10:02.273
♪

10:05.772 --> 10:06.982
Captain MacKenzie.

10:07.107 --> 10:08.857
Reporting for duty, sir.

10:08.942 --> 10:10.572
Fall in.

10:10.652 --> 10:13.612
♪

10:23.915 --> 10:25.335
JAMIE: Everyone.

10:26.292 --> 10:28.502
Take one, pass ’em around.

10:29.212 --> 10:32.382
It’s to be fastened
to yer coat or hat.

10:32.465 --> 10:35.335
Other companies will have
cockades as well.

10:35.468 --> 10:38.968
It’s the only way to tell
militia from Regulator,

10:39.055 --> 10:40.135
so it’s important ye wear it.

10:40.265 --> 10:42.485
I’ll have one of those.

10:43.643 --> 10:44.813
Isaiah.

10:44.894 --> 10:47.734
[ tense music ]

10:47.814 --> 10:50.234
♪

10:50.316 --> 10:52.936
Where’s my Alicia?
She with you?

10:53.027 --> 10:55.987
No, she’s at home.

10:56.072 --> 10:57.742
Her home was in Brownsville,

10:57.824 --> 10:59.994
not living in sin with you,
you bastard‐‐

11:00.118 --> 11:02.158
Easy now, everyone.

11:02.245 --> 11:03.835
CLAIRE:
Alicia made her decision.

11:05.165 --> 11:06.375
It’s her choice.

11:06.499 --> 11:08.579
Why don’t you stay out of this?

11:08.668 --> 11:12.378
Aye, it is a good life,
and we’re happy together.

11:12.505 --> 11:14.505
What was good for her was
to be with her family.

11:14.632 --> 11:17.222
I should have killed you
there and then,

11:17.343 --> 11:19.603
nailed your hide
to the tavern door.

11:20.972 --> 11:22.142
Enough.

11:22.223 --> 11:25.523
♪

11:27.937 --> 11:28.847
You shouldna be here.

11:28.980 --> 11:30.230
Ye helped me once.

11:30.356 --> 11:32.106
When I heard the troops
were mustering,

11:32.192 --> 11:33.862
I wished to repay ye.

11:34.527 --> 11:36.647
I see love hasn’t softened
yer hard head.

11:36.738 --> 11:39.778
♪

11:39.866 --> 11:42.906
This man is willing
to lay down his life.

11:43.036 --> 11:44.576
I’ll not turn him away.

11:44.704 --> 11:46.504
If ye canna find it
in yerselves

11:46.581 --> 11:49.631
to fight alongside him,
ye may go.

11:49.709 --> 11:52.669
♪

11:54.255 --> 11:55.875
There’s a battle to fight.

11:57.467 --> 12:01.137
This unpleasantness
between us...

12:01.221 --> 12:02.641
should be forgotten.

12:02.722 --> 12:05.892
♪

12:09.229 --> 12:11.269
Attach this to yer coat.

12:11.397 --> 12:14.187
[ dramatic music ]

12:14.275 --> 12:17.565
♪

12:28.331 --> 12:29.291
I’ve gone shooting every day
since we heard

12:29.415 --> 12:30.705
there might be a war.

12:30.792 --> 12:32.132
IAIN:
Shooting wood blocks
off a rail.

12:32.252 --> 12:34.632
I shot eight possums last week.

12:35.505 --> 12:37.425
War’s not like hunting.

12:37.507 --> 12:39.427
The deer and the possums
are not trying to kill ye.

12:40.551 --> 12:43.761
But Ma says the point of
hunting is to kill something,

12:43.888 --> 12:47.518
and the point of going to war
is to come back alive.

12:49.602 --> 12:52.772
War is killing, that’s that.

12:54.941 --> 12:55.941
[ exhales deeply ]

12:56.025 --> 12:58.565
Think of anything less,
think of yer own skin,

12:58.653 --> 13:00.953
then ye’ll be dead
by nightfall.

13:04.367 --> 13:06.407
Ye canna waver.

13:14.544 --> 13:15.544
COLONEL CHADWICK:
Your Excellency!

13:15.628 --> 13:18.048
A verbal message
from General Waddell.

13:18.131 --> 13:20.631
Two wagonloads of munitions
have been ambushed
and destroyed,

13:20.758 --> 13:22.008
and the general’s troops
were forced to retreat

13:22.135 --> 13:24.975
by a large force of rebels
led by Murtagh Fitzgibbons.

13:25.096 --> 13:28.466
And the scouts report
that the Regulators
are across the creek.

13:28.599 --> 13:31.809
Prepare the men.
We’ll engage the enemy here.

13:31.936 --> 13:34.726
♪

13:34.814 --> 13:36.024
I’ll have my men
ready themselves.

13:36.149 --> 13:39.439
♪

13:50.830 --> 13:52.410
Did you see anything
across the creek?

13:52.498 --> 13:53.828
Any sign of Murtagh?

13:53.958 --> 13:54.998
No.

13:55.126 --> 13:57.916
No, but I did see
Bryan Cranna and Lee Withers.

13:58.004 --> 14:00.514
They were with Murtagh
in Hillsborough
during the riots.

14:01.758 --> 14:04.218
Colonel, a minister come
from the other side

14:04.344 --> 14:05.684
with a petition
for the governor.

14:07.180 --> 14:08.260
A minister?

14:08.348 --> 14:09.598
The Reverend Caldwell.

14:10.433 --> 14:12.773
Reverend Caldwell...

14:12.852 --> 14:15.312
I regret we meet again
under such circumstances.

14:15.396 --> 14:17.436
Your Excellency,

14:17.523 --> 14:19.073
Colonel Fraser.

14:19.192 --> 14:22.862
Aye, a wedding is a‐a more
enjoyable occasion by far.

14:22.987 --> 14:24.027
Mm.

14:25.865 --> 14:29.365
I come in hopes
that we can settle this matter

14:29.452 --> 14:30.872
without bloodshed.

14:42.757 --> 14:43.547
Hmm.

14:43.633 --> 14:45.133
Pardon me, Reverend,

14:45.218 --> 14:47.888
if I disagree with
the assertion that I have not

14:47.970 --> 14:51.100
"lent a kind ear to the just
complaints of the people."

14:51.224 --> 14:54.944
I certainly do not consider
His Majesty’s subjects

14:55.061 --> 14:57.061
to be mere "toys"

14:57.146 --> 14:59.686
and their lives
"matters to be trifled with."

14:59.774 --> 15:02.534
Still, nevertheless,
I will do as they ask.

15:03.528 --> 15:05.608
I will consider
their grievances

15:05.738 --> 15:09.028
and convey my "candid
and speedy response"

15:09.117 --> 15:11.037
by, um, noon tomorrow.

15:12.412 --> 15:13.372
Thank you, sir.

15:13.454 --> 15:15.334
I will convey your answer,

15:15.415 --> 15:17.965
and we will await
your final response.

15:27.385 --> 15:29.475
Order the men to remain
under arms through the night.

15:29.595 --> 15:32.055
Cavalry should
keep their mounts
bridled and saddled.

15:32.140 --> 15:33.770
Your Excellency.

15:33.850 --> 15:36.060
I’ll draft a proclamation
demanding their surrender.

15:36.144 --> 15:39.614
Your Excellency, why not pursue
a parley, as they ask?

15:39.730 --> 15:41.360
Their "petition for peace,"
Colonel Fraser,

15:41.441 --> 15:42.821
was nothing but demands.

15:42.942 --> 15:44.782
It is I who will not be
"trifled with."

15:44.902 --> 15:48.282
Perhaps at least we wait
for reinforcements.

15:48.364 --> 15:51.334
No, a bold stroke is needed.

15:51.451 --> 15:52.661
To hesitate could mean defeat.

15:52.785 --> 15:54.865
I am governor of this province,

15:54.954 --> 15:57.674
and I cannot tolerate such
a blatant disregard for the law

15:57.790 --> 15:59.580
to be allowed to go unpunished.

16:02.044 --> 16:03.134
I will not.

16:04.714 --> 16:06.304
Their course is set.
So is mine.

16:06.424 --> 16:09.264
[ dramatic music ]

16:09.343 --> 16:12.643
♪

16:16.476 --> 16:17.476
Jemmy’s asleep.

16:17.560 --> 16:19.140
Thanks, Lizzie.

16:19.270 --> 16:22.150
We’re just so grateful
for your hospitality.

16:22.231 --> 16:25.151
Anything Mr. Sherston and I can
do for your Aunt Jocasta.

16:25.276 --> 16:26.486
[ door closes ]

16:26.611 --> 16:27.741
There’s talk at the tavern.

16:27.820 --> 16:29.910
The militia is preparing
for battle.

16:29.989 --> 16:32.159
The Regulators are across
the Alamance Creek.

16:32.283 --> 16:33.373
Where is that?

16:33.493 --> 16:34.873
I can show you on a map.

16:39.832 --> 16:41.672
Southwest of Hillsborough is

16:41.792 --> 16:43.542
the Great Alamance Creek.

16:43.669 --> 16:46.799
Wait.
Alamance...

16:48.090 --> 16:51.760
Something happened there.
I seem to remember...

16:51.844 --> 16:53.554
Have you ever been there?

16:53.679 --> 16:57.389
No, it just‐‐the name
sounds familiar.

16:57.517 --> 16:58.807
They say the Indians named it

16:58.893 --> 17:00.693
and that it means
"all man’s land."

17:00.811 --> 17:03.611
Something definitely
happened there.

17:03.689 --> 17:05.899
Alamance...

17:06.025 --> 17:08.895
♪

17:42.436 --> 17:45.226
[ speaking Gaelic ]

17:59.203 --> 18:02.083
♪

18:14.719 --> 18:16.929
So does God have an answer?

18:19.849 --> 18:22.059
I wasna calling on God.

18:23.644 --> 18:25.104
I was calling on
Dougal MacKenzie.

18:26.439 --> 18:27.769
Dougal?

18:30.359 --> 18:35.159
Considering how things ended
with us at Culloden...

18:35.281 --> 18:36.321
why?

18:36.449 --> 18:39.449
He was a war chief.

18:39.535 --> 18:40.985
Taught me everything I know.

18:44.957 --> 18:48.087
And I made my peace
with my uncle a long time ago.

18:50.087 --> 18:54.167
Dougal will ken
I did what I had to do...

18:54.300 --> 18:56.800
for my men, for ye.

18:58.471 --> 19:00.011
And I’ll do it all again now.

19:02.308 --> 19:03.808
I know you will.

19:06.479 --> 19:08.019
Tryon’s determined to fight.

19:09.982 --> 19:13.032
I’ve seen that look before
in men’s eyes...

19:13.152 --> 19:15.492
when they’re beyond reason
or compromise.

19:15.571 --> 19:18.321
Will Dougal help, do you think?

19:19.367 --> 19:20.827
If he can.

19:22.870 --> 19:25.500
We fought many times
together, Dougal and I,

19:25.623 --> 19:28.043
hand to hand,
back to back.

19:29.377 --> 19:30.877
After all, blood is blood.

19:32.088 --> 19:33.168
Yes.

19:33.297 --> 19:35.877
♪

19:36.008 --> 19:38.258
But there’s someone else
that you share blood with.

19:38.344 --> 19:39.934
Aye.

19:41.347 --> 19:43.387
Murtagh and I fought
back to back as well.

19:45.101 --> 19:46.601
This time,
we’ll fight face to face.

19:46.686 --> 19:49.766
♪

19:49.855 --> 19:52.065
No amount of prayer will help.

19:52.191 --> 19:55.111
♪

20:02.493 --> 20:05.373
[ tense music ]

20:05.454 --> 20:08.174
♪

20:24.932 --> 20:26.892
‐ CLAIRE: Bree?
‐ JAMIE: Aye.

20:27.017 --> 20:30.147
[ dramatic music ]

20:30.229 --> 20:33.069
♪

20:35.818 --> 20:37.738
I’ve come to warn you.

20:37.820 --> 20:40.450
The fight happens here
at the creek,

20:40.573 --> 20:41.873
and the militia will win.

20:43.617 --> 20:45.117
How many lives are lost?

20:45.244 --> 20:46.954
I don’t know numbers
or details.

20:47.079 --> 20:49.919
My professor said that
some people consider this

20:50.040 --> 20:52.080
to be the spark
of the American Revolution.

20:52.168 --> 20:54.248
But the Regulators aren’t
trying to overthrow the Crown.

20:54.378 --> 20:55.918
They aren’t fighting
for independence.

20:56.046 --> 20:57.836
No, but they are rebelling
against corruption

20:57.923 --> 20:59.593
and unfair taxes.

20:59.717 --> 21:02.467
Ye’re certain Tryon wins?

21:02.595 --> 21:04.305
Yes.

21:05.806 --> 21:07.466
[ sighs ]

21:09.685 --> 21:11.765
[ sighs ]

21:11.854 --> 21:13.774
I must get a message
to Murtagh then.

21:14.607 --> 21:17.227
If he can be warned
the Regulators are
doomed to fail,

21:17.318 --> 21:20.948
then maybe he can convince
his men to retreat

21:21.071 --> 21:23.991
and lives will be spared
on both sides.

21:24.784 --> 21:26.834
Wait.

21:26.952 --> 21:30.582
If we do stop this fight now,
what if...

21:30.664 --> 21:34.844
doesn’t that mean the
Revolutionary War won’t happen?

21:34.960 --> 21:38.090
And America will never
become America.

21:40.466 --> 21:43.966
Ye say some people believe
this is the spark.

21:45.304 --> 21:46.764
Couldn’t the spark alight
from somewhere else?

21:46.847 --> 21:49.267
Yes, it could.

21:52.311 --> 21:55.151
What matters are
the men in my charge,

21:55.272 --> 21:57.362
the Regulators fighting
for what they believe in,

21:57.483 --> 21:58.653
and my godfather.

21:58.776 --> 22:00.816
ROGER:
I agree.

22:00.945 --> 22:02.035
I’ll deliver the message
to Murtagh.

22:02.154 --> 22:04.994
[ ominous music ]

22:05.115 --> 22:06.985
It’s too dangerous.

22:07.117 --> 22:10.867
I know, but I’m the only one
that can do it.

22:10.996 --> 22:12.906
He knows me.
He knows I’m from the future.

22:12.998 --> 22:14.538
He’ll believe it.

22:14.667 --> 22:17.787
♪

22:17.878 --> 22:19.338
Yeah, all right.

22:21.173 --> 22:22.553
Ye’ll leave at nightfall.

22:24.218 --> 22:27.008
Keep this in your pocket.

22:27.096 --> 22:29.676
Then they willna see ye come
from the other side.

22:29.807 --> 22:31.427
And if ye’re threatened...

22:31.517 --> 22:34.017
♪

22:34.103 --> 22:37.813
Wave this and cry "truce"

22:37.898 --> 22:39.688
and tell them to fetch me.

22:39.817 --> 22:41.357
Dinna say more until I come.

22:41.485 --> 22:43.355
Aye.

22:43.487 --> 22:46.407
♪

22:51.537 --> 22:54.367
[ tense music ]

22:54.498 --> 22:57.378
♪

23:02.715 --> 23:06.725
Belladonna, laudanum...

23:06.844 --> 23:11.014
oil of juniper, pennyroyal,

23:11.098 --> 23:14.018
alcohol, and my secret weapon.

23:15.102 --> 23:16.902
BRIANNA:
The penicillin.

23:16.979 --> 23:19.269
If I’d had it at Prestonpans,

23:19.398 --> 23:21.568
imagine the lives
I could have saved.

23:21.650 --> 23:25.900
Maybe you’ll save some today,
and I’ll stay and help.

23:26.030 --> 23:27.570
It’ll keep me from worrying.

23:28.908 --> 23:31.618
Jamie assured us
under the flag of truce,

23:31.744 --> 23:33.164
no one will trouble Roger.

23:33.245 --> 23:35.205
Will the flag of truce
really help him

23:35.289 --> 23:37.079
if he’s still over there
when the shooting starts?

23:37.166 --> 23:39.416
If the shooting starts.

23:41.587 --> 23:44.707
Let’s just hope he manages
to convince Murtagh.

23:44.798 --> 23:46.548
[ exhales sharply ]

23:48.260 --> 23:51.100
MURTAGH:
Tryon’s left us no choice.

23:51.180 --> 23:52.930
He’s lied to us in the past!

23:53.057 --> 23:54.267
[ crowd clamoring ]

23:54.391 --> 23:57.101
MURTAGH:
We canna submit to tyranny!

23:57.227 --> 23:58.597
‐ CROWD: No!
‐ MAN: Never!

23:58.729 --> 24:01.769
MURTAGH:
We’re not resisting
law and order.

24:01.899 --> 24:03.779
We are fighting injustice!

24:03.859 --> 24:06.069
[ crowd cheers ]

24:07.780 --> 24:09.450
Tryon will regret the day

24:09.573 --> 24:12.083
that he chose to ignore
our demands.

24:13.077 --> 24:16.867
His blood will soak
this ground!

24:16.956 --> 24:20.206
[ crowd cheering ]

24:24.964 --> 24:26.844
Now go.

24:26.966 --> 24:28.966
Be ready for the morrow.

24:29.093 --> 24:32.513
[ indistinct chatter ]

24:41.730 --> 24:43.690
[ whispers ]
What the devil
are ye doing here?

24:43.816 --> 24:45.526
I need to talk to you.

24:53.701 --> 24:55.911
Murtagh, you’re going
to lose this battle.

24:55.995 --> 24:58.465
Brianna saw the name
"Alamance" on a map,

24:58.539 --> 25:01.249
and she remembered
the Regulators lose.

25:05.045 --> 25:05.995
‐ What?
‐ ROGER: Aye.

25:06.130 --> 25:07.510
Jamie wanted you to know

25:07.631 --> 25:09.971
that the best thing
that you can do is leave now,

25:10.050 --> 25:11.300
convince your men to disperse.

25:11.385 --> 25:14.555
Christ, MacKenzie,
ye saw the men.

25:16.098 --> 25:17.308
Ye think they’ll yield
in this fight?

25:17.391 --> 25:20.351
I believe that they might,
if you tell them to.

25:21.645 --> 25:24.145
If you don’t,
they’ll be slaughtered.

25:24.231 --> 25:26.361
How many men does Tryon have?

25:26.442 --> 25:28.322
‐ More than a thousand.
‐ We have twice that number.

25:28.402 --> 25:30.652
But Tryon has
a trained militia.

25:30.738 --> 25:35.158
You‐you have farmers
with knives and pitchforks.

25:35.242 --> 25:37.202
And they’re brave as lions.

25:38.328 --> 25:39.408
They’ll fight
when the time comes.

25:39.538 --> 25:41.868
Tryon has cannons,
for Chrissakes.

25:42.666 --> 25:46.036
Murtagh, most of your men
have never even seen a cannon.

25:46.128 --> 25:50.168
You have no officers,
you have no cavalry,
you have no artillery.

25:51.383 --> 25:52.803
Listen to me, man.
You cannot win.

25:52.885 --> 25:55.435
You do not win.
The history has been written.

25:56.764 --> 25:58.474
Then I do fight.

25:58.557 --> 25:59.557
[ chuckles ]

26:01.185 --> 26:03.445
How can I tell them
to cast aside

26:03.562 --> 26:06.732
everything they’ve fought for,
just give up?

26:06.857 --> 26:10.487
They’ll not be giving up.
They’ll be living
to fight another day.

26:10.569 --> 26:12.569
And if‐if they wait‐‐
if you wait,

26:12.654 --> 26:15.074
in a few years, we’ll all be
fighting on the same side.

26:15.199 --> 26:17.159
Do ye ken how long
a few years is

26:17.242 --> 26:18.992
to men who’ve lost everything?

26:19.078 --> 26:22.328
♪

26:28.212 --> 26:31.342
GOVERNOR TRYON:
To those who style
themselves Regulators...

26:33.300 --> 26:34.970
In reply to your petition...

26:35.094 --> 26:37.184
MURTAGH:
"I have been ever attentive

26:37.262 --> 26:39.562
"to the interests
of your county

26:39.640 --> 26:42.100
and to every individual
residing therein."

26:42.226 --> 26:44.056
[ scoffs ]

26:45.145 --> 26:47.605
‐ MURTAGH: "I lament..."
‐ TRYON: I lament
the fatal necessity

26:47.731 --> 26:50.441
to which you have now
reduced me...

26:50.567 --> 26:53.487
by withdrawing yourselves
from the mercy of the Crown...

26:53.612 --> 26:55.822
BOTH: "And the laws
of your country."

26:57.741 --> 27:01.241
MURTAGH:
"I require you
who are now assembled..."

27:01.328 --> 27:03.828
To lay down your arms,

27:03.956 --> 27:05.456
surrender up your leaders,

27:05.541 --> 27:08.341
and submit yourselves to the
leniency of the government.

27:08.460 --> 27:13.300
"By accepting these terms
within one hour,

27:13.423 --> 27:15.933
"you will prevent
an effusion of blood...

27:16.009 --> 27:18.219
"as you are at this time

27:18.303 --> 27:20.063
in a state of war
and rebellion..."

27:20.139 --> 27:23.809
Against your king,
your country...

27:23.892 --> 27:25.812
♪

27:25.936 --> 27:28.096
"And your laws."

27:28.188 --> 27:31.188
♪

27:31.316 --> 27:32.776
Signed, William Tryon.

27:34.027 --> 27:36.857
[ crowd murmuring ]

27:39.032 --> 27:42.332
♪

28:09.021 --> 28:10.401
I spoke wi’ the men.

28:13.108 --> 28:15.528
[ Murtagh sighs ]

28:19.031 --> 28:21.701
I tried to convince them...

28:24.661 --> 28:26.371
But they willna turn back now.

28:27.497 --> 28:29.497
This battle will happen.

28:34.171 --> 28:37.261
Ye’ve done yer best here...

28:37.382 --> 28:39.512
but it’s for ye to return
to yer own camp.

28:40.719 --> 28:43.889
Leave now...

28:44.014 --> 28:45.354
before it begins.

28:47.392 --> 28:49.892
If your men won’t,

28:49.978 --> 28:51.398
then I urge you‐‐

28:51.521 --> 28:53.901
no, Murtagh, I beg you...

28:54.024 --> 28:55.024
time is running out.

28:55.108 --> 28:56.568
Leave and save yourself.

28:57.694 --> 28:59.364
Please.

29:00.572 --> 29:02.622
For the love
your godson bears you.

29:02.741 --> 29:05.621
♪

29:07.412 --> 29:10.212
[ children giggling ]

29:10.290 --> 29:13.590
♪

29:18.757 --> 29:22.757
Morag.
Mistress MacKenzie.

29:23.762 --> 29:25.102
MORAG:
Mr. MacKenzie.

29:25.180 --> 29:28.020
♪

29:28.100 --> 29:29.770
It’s good to see you again.

29:29.851 --> 29:32.441
Are you in good health,
and your child, Jemmy?

29:32.562 --> 29:34.772
We’re well, both of us.

29:34.856 --> 29:36.316
Pleased to hear.

29:36.441 --> 29:38.321
I’ve my own son now.

29:38.443 --> 29:40.453
His name’s Jemmy,
Jeremiah, as well.

29:40.570 --> 29:42.070
It was my father’s name.

29:42.155 --> 29:43.945
’Tis a fine, strong name.

29:46.535 --> 29:47.705
I’ve thought of you
now and then.

29:47.786 --> 29:51.406
Oh, aye.
I do thank ye, Mr. MacKenzie.

29:52.165 --> 29:53.325
I’ll not forget
how ye saved us

29:53.458 --> 29:55.038
from that
heartless sea captain.

29:55.127 --> 29:57.207
Mrs. MacKenzie, wait.

29:57.296 --> 29:58.626
I’ve something I need
to tell you.

29:58.714 --> 29:59.964
Oh, I’m sorry, your laundry.
Here.

30:00.090 --> 30:01.840
‐ [ heads thud ]
‐ MORAG: Oh!
Mary and Bride!

30:01.967 --> 30:03.507
[ both sigh ]

30:03.635 --> 30:04.965
Did I hurt you?
I’m sorry.

30:05.095 --> 30:06.555
Nay.

30:06.638 --> 30:08.718
I’ve a thick skull,
my ma always said.

30:08.807 --> 30:12.227
I’ve a thick skull too,
runs in my family.

30:12.311 --> 30:13.811
[ laughs ]

30:14.730 --> 30:17.820
Your husband,
is he one of the Regulators?

30:17.899 --> 30:18.939
Aye, of course.

30:20.152 --> 30:21.612
I’m with the militia.

30:21.695 --> 30:24.575
The thing I wanted
to tell you‐‐to warn you,

30:24.656 --> 30:26.366
the governor, he’s serious.

30:26.491 --> 30:28.791
He’s brought troops.
He’s brought cannon.

30:28.869 --> 30:30.999
He means to put down this
rebellion, do you understand?

30:31.121 --> 30:35.331
You must tell your husband,
leave before anything happens.

30:35.417 --> 30:37.037
Leave and go where?

30:37.169 --> 30:39.049
♪

30:39.171 --> 30:41.131
We have no home to go back to.

30:41.214 --> 30:42.844
You’re with child.

30:42.966 --> 30:45.086
♪

30:45.177 --> 30:48.677
Look, I have to go,
but Mistress MacKenzie,
hear me.

30:48.764 --> 30:51.064
If anything should happen,
come to me.

30:51.183 --> 30:52.023
I’ll take care of you.

30:52.100 --> 30:54.310
Your family’s welcome
on Fraser’s Ridge.

30:54.394 --> 30:57.694
♪

31:00.025 --> 31:02.155
BUCK:
Get away from my wife.

31:02.235 --> 31:05.195
♪

31:05.322 --> 31:07.032
Captain MacKenzie!

31:11.203 --> 31:12.503
Anyone seen Roger Mac?

31:12.579 --> 31:14.619
No, I havena, Colonel.

31:14.706 --> 31:16.786
Not hide nor hair of him,
I’m afraid.

31:16.875 --> 31:18.955
Been hours since I laid eyes
on the captain.

31:19.044 --> 31:20.924
Christ, where is he?

31:21.046 --> 31:22.626
Colonel Fraser!

31:29.471 --> 31:31.721
[ clears throat ]

31:34.893 --> 31:36.313
Governor.

31:37.270 --> 31:39.650
I thought you’d cut
a striking figure in this.

31:41.066 --> 31:42.606
Sir?

31:42.734 --> 31:44.574
Well, you’re one
of my best officers.

31:44.653 --> 31:46.953
I’m not gonna have you mistaken
for an insurgent.

31:49.699 --> 31:50.909
I appreciate the gesture,
Your Excellency,

31:50.992 --> 31:52.912
but, uh,
I dinna think it proper

31:53.036 --> 31:56.406
for me to wear
such a...garment.

31:56.540 --> 31:59.040
You’re much too humble,
Colonel.

31:59.126 --> 32:01.706
I know that you, more than most
who will take this battlefield,

32:01.795 --> 32:03.255
are deserving of the privilege.

32:03.338 --> 32:07.928
So please...do me the honor.

32:32.033 --> 32:34.833
Ah. Yes.

32:37.622 --> 32:40.632
Yes, a striking figure indeed.

32:41.460 --> 32:42.630
Colonel Chadwick?

32:42.711 --> 32:44.211
COLONEL CHADWICK:
Company!

32:44.296 --> 32:46.166
[ shouts ]

32:46.298 --> 32:49.588
♪

33:10.739 --> 33:12.949
My apologies.
I swear I meant no disrespect.

33:13.033 --> 33:15.993
No?
Then what the hell d’ye think
you were doing then, eh?

33:16.995 --> 33:19.035
I met Mistress MacKenzie
aboard the Gloriana

33:19.164 --> 33:20.584
a year or two ago.

33:20.665 --> 33:21.995
When I recognized her here,

33:22.083 --> 33:23.963
I thought to inquire
as to the family’s welfare.

33:24.044 --> 33:26.384
‐ That’s all.
‐ He met nae harm, William.

33:26.505 --> 33:29.805
It was him who found
me and Jemmy in the hold
when we hid there.

33:29.883 --> 33:32.683
He brought us food and water.

33:32.761 --> 33:33.851
He cared for us that night

33:33.970 --> 33:36.180
when the sailors threw
the sick ones into the sea.

33:36.306 --> 33:38.306
Oh, aye?

33:38.391 --> 33:39.601
Who’s this, Buck?

33:39.684 --> 33:40.854
That’s what I mean to find out.

33:40.977 --> 33:42.557
Ye go back with the women,
Morag.

33:42.687 --> 33:44.017
I’m gonna settle
with this fella.

33:44.147 --> 33:46.687
‐ But he hasna done anything!
‐ Listen to me.

33:46.816 --> 33:48.776
Ye think it’s nothing
when a man coories into ye

33:48.860 --> 33:50.820
in public like a common radge?

33:50.904 --> 33:53.494
‐ No!
‐ Now I told ye to get back.

33:53.573 --> 33:55.583
So go now.

33:55.700 --> 33:57.200
‐ [ Morag gasps ]
‐ [ William grunts ]

33:57.327 --> 33:59.827
MORAG: William!

33:59.913 --> 34:01.213
‐ Get away from me, woman!
‐ [ Morag yelps ]

34:01.331 --> 34:03.961
[ both grunting ]

34:07.504 --> 34:08.554
[ man groans ]

34:08.672 --> 34:10.172
Get him up.

34:10.257 --> 34:13.627
[ all grunting ]

34:13.718 --> 34:16.798
[ blow lands, Roger grunts ]

34:17.722 --> 34:19.312
She’s a MacKenzie.

34:19.391 --> 34:20.931
I’m a MacKenzie.
We’re blood.

34:21.059 --> 34:23.059
That’s why I was trying
to help her.

34:23.144 --> 34:25.564
What’s this?

34:25.647 --> 34:28.067
[ ominous music ]

34:28.191 --> 34:29.901
Ye’re with the militia,
aren’t ye?

34:30.026 --> 34:32.696
I came to warn you about Tryon.

34:32.779 --> 34:35.949
Oh, so ye’re a wife‐stealer
and a traitor,

34:36.074 --> 34:37.994
all tied up in a wee bundle,
is it?

34:38.076 --> 34:41.746
Ah, slit his throat, I say,
and good riddance.

34:41.830 --> 34:43.620
A man who’s sure of his wife
needn’t worry

34:43.748 --> 34:45.788
that someone else may try
to steal her.

34:45.917 --> 34:47.747
I’m sure of my own wife
and have no need of yours.

34:47.836 --> 34:49.206
BUCK: Married, are ye?

34:49.296 --> 34:51.586
Well, yer wife must be
ill‐favored, surely,

34:51.673 --> 34:54.633
for ye to be sniffing
after mine.

34:54.759 --> 34:56.259
Or perhaps she put ye
out of her bed

34:56.344 --> 34:58.264
because ye couldn’t
serve her decently.

34:58.388 --> 35:00.428
[ growls ]

35:00.557 --> 35:04.387
You let me go, sir,
and I’ll not speak against you,

35:04.477 --> 35:06.187
for your wife’s sake.

35:07.480 --> 35:09.190
Aye.

35:09.274 --> 35:10.944
No.

35:11.067 --> 35:15.027
No.
I dinna think ye well.

35:17.532 --> 35:18.872
[ grunts ]

35:19.951 --> 35:22.291
Speak against me, that is.

35:27.292 --> 35:30.132
[ tense music ]

35:30.253 --> 35:33.133
♪

35:53.818 --> 35:56.858
Jesus H. Roosevelt Christ.

35:58.239 --> 36:00.069
Tryon...

36:02.494 --> 36:04.004
Insisted.

36:04.079 --> 36:07.789
I imagine you weren’t
in a position to refuse.

36:17.634 --> 36:20.394
[ man shouting ]

36:20.512 --> 36:22.102
There’s no sign of Roger.

36:22.180 --> 36:25.140
We dinna ken
if he succeeded or...

36:25.225 --> 36:28.485
havena heard,
but the battle is upon us.

36:28.561 --> 36:30.151
MAN: Company!

36:31.523 --> 36:33.073
Will ye wish me luck, then?

36:35.110 --> 36:38.070
I can’t let you go
without saying something.

36:38.196 --> 36:40.866
♪

36:40.949 --> 36:43.409
I suppose "good luck" will do.

36:43.535 --> 36:46.835
♪

36:47.872 --> 36:49.542
I love you, soldier.

36:49.666 --> 36:52.916
♪

36:58.758 --> 37:01.138
"Good luck" will do.

37:01.219 --> 37:03.429
"I love you"
does so much better.

37:03.555 --> 37:06.435
♪

37:07.851 --> 37:09.561
[ man shouts ]

37:09.644 --> 37:12.484
That obituary Bree brought us,
I dinna ken if it’s true.

37:12.564 --> 37:15.024
But what I do ken is this.

37:15.108 --> 37:17.358
There may come a day when
you and I shall part again,

37:17.444 --> 37:20.494
but it willna be today.

37:20.572 --> 37:22.452
[ man shouts ]

37:27.412 --> 37:30.372
♪

37:34.794 --> 37:37.674
[ dramatic music ]

37:37.756 --> 37:41.046
♪

37:50.435 --> 37:51.895
We go in hard.

37:51.978 --> 37:53.728
Protect ourselves.

37:53.813 --> 37:56.233
♪

37:56.316 --> 37:58.026
We’re not here to kill
our brothers.

37:59.611 --> 38:00.991
We’re here to end this.

38:03.239 --> 38:05.909
Put the fear of God in them,
they’ll retreat.

38:05.992 --> 38:07.952
This doesna have to be
a massacre.

38:08.036 --> 38:12.036
Take prisoners, save souls.

38:13.458 --> 38:16.498
♪

38:18.046 --> 38:21.256
Watch for MacKenzie.

38:22.300 --> 38:24.430
Cannons!

38:24.511 --> 38:25.761
MAN: Fire!

38:25.845 --> 38:28.055
[ cannon booms ]

38:35.188 --> 38:36.648
‐ [ gunshot ]
‐ [ grunts ]

38:36.731 --> 38:39.111
First line, fire!

38:39.192 --> 38:41.152
‐ Fire!
‐ [ gunshots ]

38:41.236 --> 38:42.276
Ahh!

38:42.362 --> 38:45.322
♪

38:49.661 --> 38:53.251
Fire, God damn you!
Fire on them or fire on me!

38:53.331 --> 38:57.131
♪

38:57.836 --> 38:59.206
Fire!

39:01.714 --> 39:02.634
MAN: Forward!

39:04.592 --> 39:06.512
Second rank, fire!

39:10.515 --> 39:11.435
[ grunts ]

39:11.516 --> 39:13.476
♪

39:13.560 --> 39:15.480
[ gunfire ]

39:15.562 --> 39:16.482
MAN: Forward!

39:17.814 --> 39:20.524
[ all yelling ]

39:22.360 --> 39:25.240
♪

39:31.911 --> 39:34.621
[ gunshots ]

39:34.706 --> 39:36.456
[ grunts ]

39:36.541 --> 39:39.461
♪

39:42.630 --> 39:44.720
♪

39:44.841 --> 39:48.011
[ distant gunfire ]

39:51.097 --> 39:52.887
JAMIE: Find cover!

39:52.974 --> 39:56.194
[ gunfire ]

40:08.865 --> 40:10.705
We fight as they do.

40:10.783 --> 40:13.083
Myers, with me.

40:18.666 --> 40:20.576
[ both grunting ]

40:23.880 --> 40:27.170
♪

40:35.975 --> 40:38.595
[ both panting ]

40:39.771 --> 40:41.111
[ grunts ]

40:45.693 --> 40:47.243
CLAIRE:
Come take his coat off
and his waistcoat,

40:47.320 --> 40:48.900
and I’ll come
and reassess the wound.

40:48.988 --> 40:51.868
[ dramatic music]

40:51.950 --> 40:54.620
♪

40:54.744 --> 40:55.954
Don’t worry.

40:56.079 --> 40:57.199
He was probably
just on his way back

40:57.288 --> 40:58.288
and then joined the fight.

40:58.373 --> 40:59.963
I just don’t know
which is worse:

41:00.083 --> 41:02.173
that he’s missing
or getting shot at.

41:02.961 --> 41:04.631
[ gunshot ]

41:04.712 --> 41:06.342
[ men yelling ]

41:07.966 --> 41:10.466
[ Isaiah groaning ]

41:12.637 --> 41:14.927
MAN:
Mistress Fraser.
Mistress Fraser.

41:15.014 --> 41:16.774
Isaiah!
Here.

41:16.849 --> 41:17.849
Get him up here.

41:17.976 --> 41:19.596
Easy.

41:19.686 --> 41:20.636
Let me see.

41:20.770 --> 41:22.900
He’s been shot through the lung
from behind.

41:22.981 --> 41:24.611
Here.

41:24.691 --> 41:25.821
Isaiah, can you hear me?

41:25.942 --> 41:29.242
Tell Ally I love her.

41:29.320 --> 41:31.200
You’re not going to die on me,
you hear?

41:31.322 --> 41:34.162
[ gasps ]
Baby comes next month.

41:34.283 --> 41:37.503
And you’ll be there.
Bree, get me the alcohol.

41:40.832 --> 41:42.882
‐ Ahh!
‐ [ both grunt ]

41:43.001 --> 41:45.251
[ grunting ]

41:49.674 --> 41:51.224
Come! Come on!

41:54.721 --> 41:56.011
Come on, let’s go.

41:56.097 --> 41:58.677
Come on, help him.
Let’s go, quick.

42:00.059 --> 42:01.309
[ man yells ]

42:02.311 --> 42:03.691
Ah!
[ grunts ]

42:03.813 --> 42:06.693
♪

42:06.816 --> 42:08.316
[yells ]

42:09.694 --> 42:11.574
[ exhales sharply ]

42:14.240 --> 42:15.700
RICHARD:
What’s that ye’re giving him?

42:15.783 --> 42:17.163
It’ll help him heal.

42:18.369 --> 42:19.539
[ gunshot booms distantly ]

42:21.539 --> 42:22.499
Morton.

42:26.502 --> 42:29.882
I hope you didn’t waste any
good medicine on that coward.

42:30.882 --> 42:33.432
He was running away
like a scared rabbit
when he was felled.

42:33.551 --> 42:35.761
[ strained ]
I wasna running away.

42:35.887 --> 42:37.717
Ye saw what happened.

42:37.847 --> 42:40.307
[ gasping ]

42:41.976 --> 42:43.556
Powder burns were on his back.

42:44.729 --> 42:48.399
So whoever shot him,
shot him at close range.

42:48.483 --> 42:51.243
No woman speaks to me
like that.

42:55.156 --> 42:56.736
What have you done?

42:56.866 --> 42:59.536
♪

42:59.619 --> 43:01.039
No.

43:01.120 --> 43:04.670
♪

43:10.922 --> 43:12.132
[ gunfire ]

43:12.256 --> 43:15.426
[ man yelling distantly ]

43:18.596 --> 43:21.466
♪

43:46.749 --> 43:49.629
♪

43:54.841 --> 43:55.921
[ blow falls ]

43:56.008 --> 43:59.298
♪

44:20.324 --> 44:21.744
[ blow falls ]

44:25.872 --> 44:27.412
[ gunshot ]

44:27.498 --> 44:29.708
[ panting ]
Withers!

44:29.834 --> 44:31.714
Lee Withers!

44:33.504 --> 44:35.844
For God’s sake, man,
do ye not recognize me?

44:35.965 --> 44:37.385
I mean ye no harm.

44:37.508 --> 44:40.548
Ye mean me nae harm,
but ye wear the coat
of my enemy.

44:40.678 --> 44:43.258
And yer fellows,
they‐they kill wi’out mercy.

44:43.347 --> 44:44.887
Withers, listen,
I dinna want to shoot ye.

44:47.018 --> 44:49.438
Bryan Cranna is dead.

44:52.857 --> 44:53.817
[ grunts ]

45:05.203 --> 45:06.913
[ gunshot ]

45:09.874 --> 45:12.634
I did what you said, Colonel.
I didna waver.

45:12.710 --> 45:15.670
♪

45:36.776 --> 45:38.936
[ panting ]

45:39.070 --> 45:42.360
♪

45:43.908 --> 45:47.328
I released ye from yer oath.
Ye had no cause to save me.

45:47.411 --> 45:48.791
Ye should ha’ done as I asked.

45:48.913 --> 45:51.793
[ gasping ]
I’d never betray yer mother...

45:51.916 --> 45:53.786
[ panting ]

45:53.918 --> 45:55.878
No matter who asked.

45:55.962 --> 45:58.842
[ wheezing ]

45:58.923 --> 46:01.933
♪

46:04.387 --> 46:06.217
‐ Ghoistidh.
‐ [ gasps ]

46:06.305 --> 46:09.595
♪

46:12.061 --> 46:13.351
Dinna be afraid...

46:13.437 --> 46:14.937
[ speaks Gaelic ]

46:17.191 --> 46:18.781
It doesn’t hurt a bit to die.

46:18.901 --> 46:20.901
♪

46:20.987 --> 46:21.987
[ gasps ]

46:22.113 --> 46:25.873
♪

46:25.950 --> 46:26.780
[ whimpers softly ]

46:26.909 --> 46:29.869
♪

46:31.080 --> 46:32.460
Murtagh.

46:36.794 --> 46:37.844
Murtagh.

46:37.962 --> 46:40.802
[ solemn music ]

46:40.923 --> 46:43.803
♪

46:48.889 --> 46:49.969
Help me.

46:50.099 --> 46:52.979
♪

46:55.813 --> 46:57.483
Help me.

46:58.816 --> 47:00.776
Help me!

47:00.860 --> 47:03.650
♪

47:09.618 --> 47:12.038
‐ Colonel, I‐I think he’s‐‐
‐ Help me now!

47:12.163 --> 47:15.793
♪

47:15.875 --> 47:18.175
[ panting ]

47:18.294 --> 47:21.594
♪

47:28.012 --> 47:30.392
[ speaks Gaelic ]

47:30.514 --> 47:32.894
We’ll take ye to Claire.
She’ll ken what to do.

47:33.017 --> 47:34.597
This way.

47:35.519 --> 47:37.519
All will be well.

47:39.023 --> 47:41.943
♪

47:42.026 --> 47:45.026
Claire!
Save him!

47:47.323 --> 47:49.033
[ both grunt ]

47:49.158 --> 47:50.488
What do you need?

47:52.203 --> 47:53.333
What is it?

47:53.412 --> 47:56.292
♪

47:56.374 --> 47:57.544
Here.

47:58.459 --> 48:00.839
Do what you must.
Heal him.

48:00.920 --> 48:03.840
♪

48:10.096 --> 48:11.556
I’m sorry.

48:13.891 --> 48:14.891
He’s gone.

48:15.017 --> 48:17.637
♪

48:17.728 --> 48:19.558
He canna be.
He canna.

48:19.647 --> 48:21.357
[ breathing shakily ]

48:21.440 --> 48:24.740
♪

48:26.237 --> 48:29.987
Do something.
Save him!

48:30.074 --> 48:31.244
[ breathes heavily ]

48:31.367 --> 48:34.237
♪

48:34.328 --> 48:38.668
[ panting ]
Take it back.

48:40.543 --> 48:42.253
I dinna release ye
from yer oath.

48:42.378 --> 48:45.258
♪

48:45.339 --> 48:46.919
Ye canna leave me.

48:48.384 --> 48:50.304
Ye canna leave me.

48:50.428 --> 48:53.258
[ somber music ]

48:53.347 --> 48:55.267
♪

48:55.391 --> 48:56.811
[ whispers ]
Ghoistidh.

48:56.934 --> 48:59.814
♪

49:00.938 --> 49:01.858
Jamie.

49:01.939 --> 49:05.069
♪

49:45.316 --> 49:47.106
[ sniffles ]

49:47.193 --> 49:48.193
Murtagh.

49:48.319 --> 49:50.989
♪

49:51.071 --> 49:52.491
[ sobs ]

49:52.615 --> 49:54.205
My friend.

49:54.325 --> 49:56.835
♪

49:56.952 --> 49:58.002
[ sobs ]

49:59.163 --> 50:00.333
Colonel Fraser.

50:01.832 --> 50:03.332
Victory tastes sweet,
does it not?

50:03.417 --> 50:06.997
They are finished.
We must celebrate
this glorious day.

50:08.797 --> 50:10.167
Is the slaughter
of innocent men

50:10.299 --> 50:11.679
cause to celebrate?

50:11.800 --> 50:13.470
Not sure I take your meaning,
Colonel.

50:13.552 --> 50:15.642
I meant exactly what I said.

50:17.306 --> 50:20.476
Now, I understand how difficult
it must have been

50:20.559 --> 50:22.639
to engage your own countrymen.

50:22.728 --> 50:24.808
But what we have accomplished
here today

50:24.897 --> 50:26.357
will be written about
in history.

50:26.440 --> 50:28.690
Will it be written
in history, sir,

50:28.817 --> 50:31.857
the ye killed and maimed

50:31.987 --> 50:33.947
and paid no heed
to the destruction ye left?

50:34.031 --> 50:37.951
That you brought cannon
upon your own citizens?

50:38.035 --> 50:39.035
No.

50:40.371 --> 50:42.001
No.

50:42.081 --> 50:46.081
It’ll say that ye
put down rebellion...

50:46.210 --> 50:47.460
preserved order,

50:47.545 --> 50:51.425
punished wickedness...

50:51.549 --> 50:52.879
did justice in the king’s name.

50:53.008 --> 50:55.218
But ye and I both know
what happened here.

50:56.095 --> 50:58.725
There is the law
and there is what is done.

50:59.890 --> 51:02.730
What ye have done
is kindle a war

51:02.851 --> 51:04.441
for the sake of your own glory.

51:04.562 --> 51:07.112
I had no personal stake
in this,

51:07.231 --> 51:11.861
no need to glorify
my own exploits, as you put it.

51:11.944 --> 51:13.074
None?

51:13.988 --> 51:16.408
So you have the governorship
of New York.

51:16.490 --> 51:18.620
I told you‐‐

51:18.742 --> 51:21.752
I told you I would not leave
North Carolina

51:21.870 --> 51:24.040
in a state of disorder
and rebellion.

51:25.874 --> 51:28.504
Now I have done
what I have done

51:28.586 --> 51:30.706
as a matter of duty.

51:31.547 --> 51:33.297
And because you have done

51:33.424 --> 51:37.184
your duty as promised...

51:37.261 --> 51:41.771
I am going to overlook
your insolence.

51:42.933 --> 51:44.063
Aye.

51:46.395 --> 51:50.115
I’ve paid my debt...

51:50.232 --> 51:53.112
and I’m finished
with my obligation to you
and to the Crown.

52:01.619 --> 52:03.039
You may have
your coat back, sir.

52:23.515 --> 52:26.805
♪

52:30.314 --> 52:32.484
[ exhales sharply ]

52:32.566 --> 52:35.936
♪

52:38.864 --> 52:40.034
[ exhales sharply ]

52:40.157 --> 52:43.027
♪

52:51.251 --> 52:52.131
[ sniffles ]

52:52.211 --> 52:55.171
♪

53:41.552 --> 53:42.512
Roger?

53:53.522 --> 53:54.982
[ grunts ]

53:55.858 --> 53:58.778
[ horses whinny ]

53:58.902 --> 54:01.702
[ dramatic music ]

54:01.780 --> 54:05.080
♪

54:05.743 --> 54:09.253
Ah!
[ grunting ]

54:09.371 --> 54:12.581
♪

54:13.083 --> 54:14.633
CLAIRE: Have you seen
Captain MacKenzie?

54:14.752 --> 54:17.962
[ man groaning ]

54:19.798 --> 54:23.088
♪

54:28.265 --> 54:30.555
BRIANNA: Have you seen
Roger MacKenzie?

54:30.642 --> 54:32.272
Are you sure?

54:33.020 --> 54:35.060
MAN: Roger MacKenzie!

54:48.452 --> 54:49.492
JAMIE:
Colonel.

54:49.620 --> 54:52.330
♪

54:52.456 --> 54:55.416
What happened here?
Why did ye hang these men?

54:55.501 --> 54:58.801
Regulator prisoners.
Tryon ordered their execution.

54:59.630 --> 55:01.630
Have ye seen
Captain MacKenzie
of Fraser’s Ridge?

55:01.757 --> 55:03.257
No, Colonel, I have not.

55:03.342 --> 55:05.642
BRIANA: Have you seen
Captain MacKenzie?

55:06.220 --> 55:08.310
Have you seen
Captain MacKenzie?

55:09.097 --> 55:11.137
Have ye seen Captain MacKenzie?

55:20.442 --> 55:23.652
♪

55:23.737 --> 55:25.317
Roger?

55:41.797 --> 55:43.297
Bree.

55:44.716 --> 55:46.676
[ speaks Gaelic ]

55:46.760 --> 55:50.010
♪
